---
import ArticleLayout from "../../layouts/ArticleLayout.astro";

const title = "BC PNP Calculator FAQ & Troubleshooting Guide 2026";
const description =
  "The ultimate troubleshooting guide for the BC PNP calculator. Fix 'score drops', screen vague error messages, and learn how to calculate your points manually with our printable worksheet.";
---

<ArticleLayout slug="bc-pnp-calculator-faq" datePublished="2026-01-29" dateModified="2026-02-09" keywords="BC PNP calculator FAQ, BC PNP questions, BC PNP score questions" title={title} description={description}>
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 sm:py-20">
    <!-- Hero Header -->
    <header class="mb-16 text-center">
      <div
        class="inline-flex items-center justify-center w-20 h-20 bg-gradient-to-br from-amber-500 to-orange-600 rounded-3xl mb-8 shadow-xl shadow-amber-200"
      >
        <svg
          class="w-10 h-10 text-white"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
        >
          <path
            stroke-linecap="round"
            stroke-linejoin="round"
            stroke-width="2"
            d="M8.228 9c.549-1.165 2.03-2 3.772-2 2.21 0 4 1.343 4 3 0 1.4-1.278 2.575-3.006 2.907-.542.104-.994.54-.994 1.093m0 3h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"
          ></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <h1
        class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-black text-slate-900 tracking-tight leading-tight mb-6"
      >
        <span
          class="text-transparent bg-clip-text bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-600 to-orange-600"
          >FAQ</span
        > & Troubleshooting
      </h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-slate-600 max-w-2xl mx-auto leading-relaxed">
        Got stuck? Here is the definitive manual for fixing calculator errors,
        understanding tricky rules, and verifying your score manually.
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- Main Content -->
    <div class="space-y-16">
      <!-- Troubleshooting Section -->
      <section>
        <div
          class="bg-gradient-to-b from-red-50 to-white rounded-[2rem] p-8 sm:p-10 border border-red-100"
        >
          <div class="text-center mb-10">
            <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-3">
              Error Message Dictionary
            </h2>
            <p class="text-slate-600">
              Translation of common calculator warnings.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-4">
            <div
              class="bg-white p-6 rounded-[1.5rem] shadow-sm border-l-4 border-red-500"
            >
              <h3 class="font-black text-slate-900 text-lg mb-2">
                "My score dropped by 10 points."
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed text-sm">
                <strong>Check this:</strong> Did you cross a wage threshold? Wages
                like $24.99 and $25.00 are in different brackets. Also check your
                "District" selection. Area 1 (Vancouver) gives 0 points, but Area
                2 (Squamish, Abbotsford) gives 5. See our <a href="/articles/bc-pnp-regional-priorities" class="text-amber-700 hover:underline">regional priorities guide</a> for area details.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div
              class="bg-white p-6 rounded-[1.5rem] shadow-sm border-l-4 border-red-500"
            >
              <h3 class="font-black text-slate-900 text-lg mb-2">
                "I can't find my University on the list."
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed text-sm">
                <strong>Fix:</strong> BC PNP doesn't have a dropdown of universities.
                You simply select "Bachelor's Degree" or "Master's Degree". Only <em
                  >where</em
                > you got it matters (BC vs. Canada vs. Foreign).
              </p>
            </div>

            <div
              class="bg-white p-6 rounded-[1.5rem] shadow-sm border-l-4 border-red-500"
            >
              <h3 class="font-black text-slate-900 text-lg mb-2">
                "The wage slider is stuck."
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed text-sm">
                <strong>Fix:</strong> Ensure you are entering the <em>hourly</em
                > rate. If you only know your annual salary, divide it by 52 weeks
                and then by your standard weekly hours (usually 40).
              </p>
            </div>

            <div
              class="bg-white p-6 rounded-[1.5rem] shadow-sm border-l-4 border-red-500"
            >
              <h3 class="font-black text-slate-900 text-lg mb-2">
                "My Directly Related Experience isn't counting."
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed text-sm">
                <strong>Fix:</strong> The calculator assumes all entered experience
                is "Directly Related". If you are switching careers (e.g., Accountant
                becoming a Web Developer), you generally cannot count your past experience.
                You must manually enter "0 years" if your past work doesn't match
                your new BC PNP job offer.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div
              class="bg-white p-6 rounded-[1.5rem] shadow-sm border-l-4 border-red-500"
            >
              <h3 class="font-black text-slate-900 text-lg mb-2">
                "Wage below minimum threshold"
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed text-sm">
                <strong>Fix:</strong> BC PNP has minimum wage requirements for certain
                streams (often $26.44/hr or family supporting wage). Ensure your entered
                hourly rate meets the specific stream criteria.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div
              class="bg-white p-6 rounded-[1.5rem] shadow-sm border-l-4 border-red-500"
            >
              <h3 class="font-black text-slate-900 text-lg mb-2">
                "Language Test Expired"
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed text-sm">
                <strong>Fix:</strong> IELTS and CELPIP results are valid for <strong
                  >2 years</strong
                >. If your test is older than that, the calculator (and the BC
                PNP) will reject it. You must retake the test. See our <a href="/articles/bc-pnp-language-requirements" class="text-amber-700 hover:underline">language requirements guide</a> for details.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Manual Calculation Worksheet -->
      <section>
        <div class="bg-slate-900 text-white rounded-[2rem] p-8 sm:p-12">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-black mb-6 border-b border-slate-700 pb-4">
            Manual Calculation Worksheet
          </h2>
          <p class="mb-6 text-slate-300">
            Don't trust the computer? Calculate it yourself on paper.
          </p>

          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 text-sm">
            <div>
              <h3
                class="text-amber-500 font-bold mb-3 uppercase tracking-widest"
              >
                Human Capital (120 Max)
              </h3>
              <ul class="space-y-4">
                <li class="flex justify-between border-b border-slate-700 pb-2">
                  <span>Directly Related Experience</span>
                  <span class="text-slate-400">_____ / 40</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex justify-between border-b border-slate-700 pb-2">
                  <span>Highest Education</span>
                  <span class="text-slate-400">_____ / 40</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex justify-between border-b border-slate-700 pb-2">
                  <span>Language (CLB)</span>
                  <span class="text-slate-400">_____ / 40</span>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3
                class="text-blue-500 font-bold mb-3 uppercase tracking-widest"
              >
                Economic Factors (80 Max)
              </h3>
              <ul class="space-y-4">
                <li class="flex justify-between border-b border-slate-700 pb-2">
                  <span>Hourly Wage</span>
                  <span class="text-slate-400">_____ / 55</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex justify-between border-b border-slate-700 pb-2">
                  <span>Area of Employment</span>
                  <span class="text-slate-400">_____ / 25</span>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div
            class="mt-8 pt-8 border-t-2 border-slate-700 flex justify-between items-center"
          >
            <span class="text-xl font-bold">TOTAL SCORE</span>
            <span class="text-4xl font-black text-amber-500">_____ / 200</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Niche Scenarios FAQ -->
      <section>
        <div class="text-center mb-10">
          <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-3">
            Niche Scenarios & Edge Cases
          </h2>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <!-- Category: Wages -->
          <h3
            class="font-bold text-slate-500 uppercase tracking-widest text-sm pl-4 mt-8 mb-4"
          >
            Wage & Salary Complexities
          </h3>

          <details
            class="group bg-white rounded-[1.5rem] border border-slate-200 overflow-hidden shadow-sm"
          >
            <summary
              class="flex justify-between items-center p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"
            >
              <span class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-lg pr-4"
                >Can I include commission/tips in my wage points?</span
              >
              <span
                class="w-8 h-8 bg-amber-100 rounded-full flex-shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center text-amber-600 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"
              >
                <svg
                  class="w-4 h-4"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                  ><path
                    stroke-linecap="round"
                    stroke-linejoin="round"
                    stroke-width="2"
                    d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg
                >
              </span>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
              <p>
                No. BC PNP uses your <strong>guaranteed base wage</strong> only. Bonuses,
                overtime, tips, profit-sharing, and commissions are excluded unless
                guaranteed in the employment contract as a fixed minimum.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details
            class="group bg-white rounded-[1.5rem] border border-slate-200 overflow-hidden shadow-sm"
          >
            <summary
              class="flex justify-between items-center p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"
            >
              <span class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-lg pr-4"
                >I work a split shift or irregular hours. How do I calculate?</span
              >
              <span
                class="w-8 h-8 bg-amber-100 rounded-full flex-shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center text-amber-600 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"
              >
                <svg
                  class="w-4 h-4"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                  ><path
                    stroke-linecap="round"
                    stroke-linejoin="round"
                    stroke-width="2"
                    d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg
                >
              </span>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
              <p>
                You must be a full-time employee (average 30+ hours/week).
                Convert your annual guaranteed income into an hourly equivalent
                based on a standard work year (1560-2080 hours), but be careful:
                BC PNP officers will look at your paystubs to verify the <em
                  >hours worked</em
                > match the claim.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <!-- Category: Experience -->
          <h3
            class="font-bold text-slate-500 uppercase tracking-widest text-sm pl-4 mt-8 mb-4"
          >
            Work Experience Gaps
          </h3>

          <details
            class="group bg-white rounded-[1.5rem] border border-slate-200 overflow-hidden shadow-sm"
          >
            <summary
              class="flex justify-between items-center p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"
            >
              <span class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-lg pr-4"
                >Does maternity/paternity leave count as experience?</span
              >
              <span
                class="w-8 h-8 bg-amber-100 rounded-full flex-shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center text-amber-600 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"
              >
                <svg
                  class="w-4 h-4"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                  ><path
                    stroke-linecap="round"
                    stroke-linejoin="round"
                    stroke-width="2"
                    d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg
                >
              </span>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
              <p>
                Generally, leave periods where you are not performing duties do <strong
                  >not</strong
                > count toward the years of experience points. However, your employment
                status remains "employed," so it doesn't break your continuity of
                employment.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details
            class="group bg-white rounded-[1.5rem] border border-slate-200 overflow-hidden shadow-sm"
          >
            <summary
              class="flex justify-between items-center p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"
            >
              <span class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-lg pr-4"
                >I worked part-time during university. Does it count?</span
              >
              <span
                class="w-8 h-8 bg-amber-100 rounded-full flex-shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center text-amber-600 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"
              >
                <svg
                  class="w-4 h-4"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                  ><path
                    stroke-linecap="round"
                    stroke-linejoin="round"
                    stroke-width="2"
                    d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg
                >
              </span>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
              <p>
                <strong>Maybe.</strong> Student work experience <em>can</em> count
                if it was paid, continuous, and at a skilled level (TEER 0, 1, 2,
                or 3). Part-time hours count pro-rata (e.g., 20 hours/week for 2 years
                = 1 year full-time). Co-op terms can also count if paid and skilled.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details
            class="group bg-white rounded-[1.5rem] border border-slate-200 overflow-hidden shadow-sm"
          >
            <summary
              class="flex justify-between items-center p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"
            >
              <span class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-lg pr-4"
                >Does self-employed experience count?</span
              >
              <span
                class="w-8 h-8 bg-amber-100 rounded-full flex-shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center text-amber-600 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"
              >
                <svg
                  class="w-4 h-4"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                  ><path
                    stroke-linecap="round"
                    stroke-linejoin="round"
                    stroke-width="2"
                    d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg
                >
              </span>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
              <p>
                Only if you can prove it with third-party evidence (contracts,
                invoices, annual tax returns). Letters from yourself or a
                partner are not accepted. The experience must also be directly
                related to your BC job offer.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details
            class="group bg-white rounded-[1.5rem] border border-slate-200 overflow-hidden shadow-sm"
          >
            <summary
              class="flex justify-between items-center p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"
            >
              <span class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-lg pr-4"
                >I work remotely for a BC company. Am I eligible?</span
              >
              <span
                class="w-8 h-8 bg-amber-100 rounded-full flex-shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center text-amber-600 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"
              >
                <svg
                  class="w-4 h-4"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                  ><path
                    stroke-linecap="round"
                    stroke-linejoin="round"
                    stroke-width="2"
                    d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg
                >
              </span>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
              <p>
                <strong>Conditional Yes.</strong> You must reside in BC. If you live
                outside BC (even elsewhere in Canada) while working for a BC company,
                you are <strong>not</strong> eligible. The program is for people settling
                in BC.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details
            class="group bg-white rounded-[1.5rem] border border-slate-200 overflow-hidden shadow-sm"
          >
            <summary
              class="flex justify-between items-center p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"
            >
              <span class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-lg pr-4"
                >Can I change employers after I apply?</span
              >
              <span
                class="w-8 h-8 bg-amber-100 rounded-full flex-shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center text-amber-600 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"
              >
                <svg
                  class="w-4 h-4"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                  ><path
                    stroke-linecap="round"
                    stroke-linejoin="round"
                    stroke-width="2"
                    d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg
                >
              </span>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
              <p>
                <strong>Risky.</strong> You must notify BC PNP immediately. If the
                new job meets all criteria and the employer signs the forms, it might
                be allowed. However, if the new job has a lower wage or different
                location that affects your score below the cutoff, your nomination
                will be cancelled.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details
            class="group bg-white rounded-[1.5rem] border border-slate-200 overflow-hidden shadow-sm"
          >
            <summary
              class="flex justify-between items-center p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"
            >
              <span class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-lg pr-4"
                >I got a promotion. Do I update my NOC?</span
              >
              <span
                class="w-8 h-8 bg-amber-100 rounded-full flex-shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center text-amber-600 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"
              >
                <svg
                  class="w-4 h-4"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                  ><path
                    stroke-linecap="round"
                    stroke-linejoin="round"
                    stroke-width="2"
                    d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg
                >
              </span>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
              <p>
                If your duties have changed significantly, you effectively have
                a new job offer. You must update your registration or
                application. Ensure the new NOC code is still eligible and that
                you meet the <a href="/articles/bc-pnp-job-offer-requirements-2026" class="text-amber-600 hover:underline">job offer requirements</a> for it.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details
            class="group bg-white rounded-[1.5rem] border border-slate-200 overflow-hidden shadow-sm"
          >
            <summary
              class="flex justify-between items-center p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"
            >
              <span class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-lg pr-4"
                >I am on Implied (Maintained) Status. Can I apply?</span
              >
              <span
                class="w-8 h-8 bg-amber-100 rounded-full flex-shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center text-amber-600 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"
              >
                <svg
                  class="w-4 h-4"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                  ><path
                    stroke-linecap="round"
                    stroke-linejoin="round"
                    stroke-width="2"
                    d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg
                >
              </span>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
              <p>
                <strong>Yes.</strong> As long as you have proof that you applied for
                a work permit extension before your previous one expired, you are
                legally allowed to work and can register/apply to BC PNP.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details
            class="group bg-white rounded-[1.5rem] border border-slate-200 overflow-hidden shadow-sm"
          >
            <summary
              class="flex justify-between items-center p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"
            >
              <span class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-lg pr-4"
                >Does severance pay count towards income?</span
              >
              <span
                class="w-8 h-8 bg-amber-100 rounded-full flex-shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center text-amber-600 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"
              >
                <svg
                  class="w-4 h-4"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                  ><path
                    stroke-linecap="round"
                    stroke-linejoin="round"
                    stroke-width="2"
                    d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg
                >
              </span>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
              <p>
                <strong>No.</strong> Severance packages are not employment income
                for the purpose of BC PNP wage points or income thresholds. Only earnings
                from active employment count.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Glossary -->
      <section>
        <div class="text-center mb-10">
          <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-3">
            BC PNP Glossary
          </h2>
        </div>

        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
          <div class="bg-slate-50 p-6 rounded-[1.5rem]">
            <p class="font-black text-slate-900 mb-1">SIRS</p>
            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">
              Skills Immigration Registration System. The "pool" where your
              points are calculated.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-slate-50 p-6 rounded-[1.5rem]">
            <p class="font-black text-slate-900 mb-1">ITA</p>
            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">
              Invitation to Apply. The "golden ticket" you get if your score is
              high enough.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-slate-50 p-6 rounded-[1.5rem]">
            <p class="font-black text-slate-900 mb-1">NOC</p>
            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">
              National Occupational Classification. The code that defines your
              job duties. See our <a href="/articles/bc-pnp-noc-codes-teer-categories-guide-2026" class="text-amber-600 hover:underline">NOC codes and TEER guide</a>.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-slate-50 p-6 rounded-[1.5rem]">
            <p class="font-black text-slate-900 mb-1">TEER</p>
            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">
              Training, Education, Experience, Responsibility. The category
              (0-5) of your NOC code.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-slate-50 p-6 rounded-[1.5rem]">
            <p class="font-black text-slate-900 mb-1">CLB</p>
            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">
              Canadian Language Benchmark. The standard scale for English/French
              proficiency.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-slate-50 p-6 rounded-[1.5rem]">
            <p class="font-black text-slate-900 mb-1">Indeterminate</p>
            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">
              A permanent job offer with no set end date.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Related Articles -->
      <section>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-[2rem] p-8 sm:p-10 border border-slate-200">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-4">Related Articles</h2>
          <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm">
            <li>
              <a href="/articles/bc-pnp-points-calculator-guide" class="text-amber-600 hover:underline font-bold">Points Calculator Guide</a>
              <span class="text-slate-500"> — Detailed breakdown of how BC PNP points are calculated</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <a href="/articles/bc-pnp-work-experience-requirements-2026" class="text-amber-600 hover:underline font-bold">Work Experience Requirements</a>
              <span class="text-slate-500"> — Rules for counting your work experience toward BC PNP</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <a href="/articles/bc-pnp-common-mistakes" class="text-amber-600 hover:underline font-bold">Common Application Mistakes</a>
              <span class="text-slate-500"> — Avoid the most frequent errors that lead to refusals</span>
            </li>
            <li>
